2026-07-03T06:32:44Z UTC
Change: Added a fully isolated demo business account with a one-time historical backfill plus a continuous background "live traffic" generator, so dashboards always show fresh, growing, realistic activity while the dev server runs, per explicit user request ("create a stream that should always add some test data in real time").
Investigation: The existing `dev_seed.rs` fixture (used by both `main.rs` startup and `checklist_tests.rs`) could not safely be extended — `checklist_tests.rs` makes hard exact-list assertions (`assert_eq!(product_ids, vec![PRODUCT_ONE_ID.to_string()])` etc.) against that exact fixture's business/units, so adding bulk transactions there would very likely break `cargo test`, which cannot be run locally in this sandbox (no Rust toolchain) to verify. Built a new, fully separate module instead: new UUID namespace (`30000000-...` vs. the existing fixture's `10000000-...`), new users/business/shops/products, never referenced by `checklist_tests.rs`, so it carries zero risk to the test suite.
Implementation: New `mbam-api/src/dev_demo_data.rs`. `seed_demo_business(db)` runs once at startup (gated `config.app_env == "development"`, same as the existing seed): idempotent upserts of a master owner, business admin, 3 shop managers, and 3 cashiers (all `*.demo@mbam.local`) across a 3-shop "Mbam Demo Retail Group" business with 12 products (Groceries/Electronics, the only two categories with i18n coverage), then deletes and rebuilds a 20-day historical transaction backfill (tagged `idempotency_key like 'demo-seed-backfill-%'`, rebuilt relative to "now" on every restart so it never goes stale). `spawn_demo_traffic_worker(db)` is a `tokio::spawn` background loop (mirroring the existing `keycloak_sync::service::spawn_worker` pattern) that inserts one new realistic transaction every 75 seconds for the life of the server, tagged `demo-live-<uuid>` so these rows are never deleted and accumulate across restarts. Both paths share a deterministic field generator (`demo_transaction_fields`) that varies customer name, payment method, line items/quantities, and occasional pending/refunded status via modulo arithmetic on a sequence counter — no `rand` dependency, fully reproducible. Wired into `main.rs`: `mod dev_demo_data;`, `seed_demo_business` called right after the existing `dev_seed::seed_test_accounts` inside the same `if config.app_env == "development"` block (non-fatal `tracing::warn!` on error), and `spawn_demo_traffic_worker` called after `AppState::new`, gated the same way.
Files changed: `mbam-api/src/dev_demo_data.rs` (new), `mbam-api/src/main.rs`.
Verification: No Rust toolchain available in this sandbox (`cargo`/`rustc` not installed, apt/rustup blocked without root or outbound network), so verification was manual: every SQL statement's columns/types were cross-checked line-by-line against the actual migrations (`0001_initial_schema.sql`, `0005_products.sql`, `0006_transactions.sql`, `0008_product_unit_scope.sql`) and against `dev_seed.rs`'s already-proven-working equivalent upsert helpers (column names, `on conflict` targets, and check-constraint-safe value ranges all match). Confirmed `products.business_unit_id` is NOT NULL with a unique `(business_unit_id, lower(sku))` index (all 12 demo SKUs are unique per shop). Confirmed `transactions`/`transaction_lines` CHECK constraints (`total_amount > 0`, `outstanding_amount >= 0 and <= total_amount`, `quantity > 0`, payment_method/payment_status/status enums) are satisfiable by every code path, including the refunded case (which forces `payment_status = 'paid'`, `outstanding_amount = 0`, never both refunded and pending). Switched a `DateTime<Utc>` construction from `Utc.from_utc_datetime(&naive)` (needs a `TimeZone` import) to `naive.and_utc()` (simpler, matches no existing pattern in the repo but is the current non-deprecated chrono 0.4.45 idiom — confirmed the resolved version in `Cargo.lock`). Confirmed `state.db` is the same `PgPool` type already passed identically to `keycloak_sync::service::spawn_worker`.
Checks not run: `cargo check`/`cargo test`/`cargo clippy` (no Rust toolchain in this sandbox — this is the real verification gate; the repo's `validate-and-merge-codex.yml` workflow only triggers on PRs from `codex/`-prefixed branches, not direct pushes to `main`, so this change relies on the user or a follow-up PR running `cargo check` to catch anything this manual review missed). No live browser verification (no local Docker/Keycloak stack in this sandbox).
Remaining risks: This is new, unexercised Rust code with no local compiler check — the highest-risk spots are the 15-argument `insert_transaction_with_lines` positional call sites (a silently-miscompiled argument order would not necessarily fail at the type level if two adjacent args share a type) and the `static PRODUCTS` slice indexing in `demo_transaction_fields` (`unit_products[(sequence as usize + line_index) % unit_products.len()]` — safe by construction since every `unit_index` 0/1/2 has 4 products in `PRODUCTS`, but worth a second look if products are ever added/removed unevenly across shops). Demo login credentials (development-only, never for production data): `master.demo@mbam.local` / `DemoMaster123`, `admin.demo@mbam.local` / `DemoAdmin123`, `manager1-3.demo@mbam.local` / `DemoManager123`, `cashier1-3.demo@mbam.local` / `DemoCashier123`.
